            <h2>Everyday Use</h2>
            <p>

                Most of the time you simply type what you want in natural language and Claude Code does the work &mdash; reading files, editing code, running commands, and asking for permission before anything risky. Alongside plain prompts, there are built-in slash commands that control the session:
                <ul>
                    <li><code>/help</code> &mdash; show available commands</li>
                    <li><code>/clear</code> &mdash; start a fresh conversation and reset context</li>
                    <li><code>/init</code> &mdash; generate a CLAUDE.md file documenting your project</li>
                    <li><code>/review</code> &mdash; review a pull request or your working changes</li>
                    <li><code>/config</code> &mdash; open settings (theme, model, and more)</li>
                    <li><code>/model</code> &mdash; switch the Claude model in use</li>
                </ul>
                Two tips that make a big difference:
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>CLAUDE.md</strong> &mdash; a file in your repo where you record project conventions, commands, and context. Claude Code reads it automatically so you don't have to repeat yourself.</li>
                    <li><strong>Plan mode</strong> &mdash; ask Claude to plan before it edits, so you can approve the approach on larger tasks before any code changes.</li>
                </ul>

            </p>
